Financial Time Series Models

Author

Xiaojing Ni

Water treatment provider

Due to the climate change and human activities, extreme climate and environment events, such as the water crisis caused by eutrophication in City of Toledo, OH, occur more frequently (Climate change indicators), and may be regularly. This phenomenon brings opportunities for environmental companies such as water treatment firm. Xylem Inc. is a large American water technology provider, in public utility, residential, commercial, agricultural and industrial settings. The company was founded in 2011 and does business in more than 150 countries (Wiki). In this report, the stock of Xylem was modeled using financial time series models, such as ARMA+GARCH to forecast the volatility of future returns.

Xylem stock prices

Figure 1 shows the plot of Xylem stock prices from 2011 to 2023. We can see the price has increased more than triple since 2014. Figure 2 shows the return plot, where we can see time-varying volatility in the data series.

Code 
## read data since 2011
xyl <- getSymbols("XYL",auto.assign = FALSE, from = "2011-10-14",src="yahoo")
xyl$date<-as.Date(xyl$date,"%Y-%m-%d")

chartSeries(xyl, theme = chartTheme("white"), # Theme
            bar.type = "hlc",  # High low close 
            up.col = "green",  # Up candle color
            dn.col = "red")   # Down candle color)


xyl.close<- Ad(xyl)
Code 
returns = diff(log(xyl.close))

chartSeries(returns, theme="white")

ACF and PACF of returns

Figure 3 and Figure 4 show the ACF and PACF plots for returns and square of returns, respectively. We can see the returns are not stationary and the error is fading. Thus, before fitting any advanced model, differencing is needed. The first differencing is performed in Figure 5. p can be in range 0-7, while q can be in range 0-7.

Code 
acf(returns, na.action = na.pass)
pacf(returns, na.action = na.pass)
Code 
acf(returns^2, na.action = na.pass)
pacf(returns^2, na.action = na.pass)
Code 
######### First Differencing#########
returns %>% diff() %>% ggtsdisplay() 


####### Second order Differencing ########

## not making much difference

Choose ARIMA model

Fitting ARIMA model

  1. Manualy fit ARIMA model.
ARIMA <- list() ## set counter
cc <- 1

temp= data.frame()
ls=matrix(rep(NA,6*192),nrow=192)

for (p in 0:7) {
  for (q in 0:7)
  {
    for (d in 0:2){
      if(p+d+q<=12)
            {
              skip_to_next <- FALSE
              model<- tryCatch({
      Arima(returns, order=c(p,d,q))
    }, error = function(e) { skip_to_next <<- TRUE})
  if(skip_to_next) { next }
              ls[cc,]= c(p,d,q,model$aic,model$bic,model$aicc)
              cc <- cc + 1
              #print(i)
              }
    }
  }
} 
temp= as.data.frame(ls)
names(temp)= c("p","d","q","AIC","BIC","AICc")


temp[which.min(temp$AIC),]#2,0,6

Both ARIMA(2,0,2) and ARIMA(3,0,3) look ok. Based on the law of parsimony, ARIMA(2,0,2) is chosen. The residuals show around 500 and 2100, 2600, there are volatility, so further model is needed.

GARCH(p,q)

Figure 6 shows the residual ACF and PACF plots after fitting ARIMA(2,0,2) model. The p ranges from 1 to 6, while q ranges from 1 to 8.

Code 
arma = Arima(returns, order=c(2,0,2)) 
arma.re= arma$residuals


acf(arma.re^2) #q=1, 8
pacf(arma.re^2) #p=1, 6
model <- list() ## set counter
cc <- 1
for (p in 1:6) {
  for (q in 1:8) {
  
model[[cc]] <- garch(arma.re,order=c(q,p),trace=F)
cc <- cc + 1
}
} 

## get AIC values for model evaluation
GARCH_AIC <- sapply(model, AIC) ## model with lowest AIC is the best
which(GARCH_AIC == min(GARCH_AIC))
[1] 1
model[[which(GARCH_AIC == min(GARCH_AIC))]]

Call:
garch(x = arma.re, order = c(q, p), trace = F)

Coefficient(s):
       a0         a1         b1  
1.705e-05  8.628e-02  8.525e-01

Best GARCH model is GARCH(1,1).

Thus, our final model is ARMA(2,2)+GARCH(1,1) as the summary shown below.

Code 
summary(fit <- garchFit(~arma(2,2)+garch(1,1),returns,trace = F))

Model equation

\(\phi(B) x_t = \delta + \theta(B) y_t\),

where \(\phi(B)=(1.922e{-03})-B-0.5567*B^2\); and \(\theta(B)=(1.922e{-03})+0.9767* B+0.5637*B^2\)

\(y_t=\sigma_t \epsilon_t\)

\(var(y_t|y_{t-1})=\sigma ^2= 1.757e{-05}+ 0.08776*(y_{t-1})^2 + 0.8491 \sigma_{t-1}^2\)
